Text.Value: Truly? Then you're made of sterner stuff than I, friend.
Leave.
I didn't catch your name.
While you're wearing that fiasco of an outfit there's only so much I can do, darling. But fine.
I must say... I'm damned lucky you showed up when you did. Can you believe what that monster was doing?
I sell anything and everything needed to cultivate your countenance.
That was a bit rude.
Hah, if looks could kill, Lord Gortash would've already hanged me. I wouldn't worry too much, this is undoubtedly some rumour cooked up by my many rivals.
It's not a rumour, you're literally named on a list of targets. Other people on it have already died.
A certain... Ineffable quality - beauty. In its many forms.
What are you selling?
A depraved mind will resort to terrible things.
Who would spread such a horrible rumour about you?
Well, I suppose if it's that elaborate a prank it rules out my sister as the culprit.
I'm glad you feel lucky. Do you also feel a deserving discount coming on?
I'll confess, it terrified me greatly... Can you imagine dressing entirely in red? Hah!
Don't be rude! I don't want to get blood on an expensive suit.
You're in danger. A killer is after you.
Jests aside - thank you. You forever have my humblest gratitude and a most generous discount on my wares.
You appear to be lost, dear. I specialise in fashion, not potato sacks.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Figaro gives you a once over

Text.Value: Leave.
Well, the feeling is decidedly mutual. Her wares are a poor imitation of the clothing I have on offer here.
Figaro Facemaker. Born Figaro Pennygood, but father thought it best to take on the business' name when in charge of it.
What's rude, dear, is strolling into a place like this looking like that.
Yes, how very rude of me... Wearing Carmen's tripe-garbs is much worse.
In the face of such horror, I don't see that I have much choice. Now, how may I help you today?
I'm just here to alter my appearance.
Well, I'm not sure... Discounts are reserved for only the most loyal customers...
If she would just accept my offer to work here, like father wanted, we could resolve all this bad blood. But no. Too proud.
Well, my sister, for one. She can be a real piece of work - no doubt jealous of my success. But it seems too elaborate for her, I must say...
Leave.
Oi! What's wrong with street detritus?
I met your sister. She didn't have a very high opinion of you.
*News of your good deeds has travelled fast. The merchant is all too happy to extend a certain generosity towards you, where the price of goods is concerned.*
The best you'll find in Baldur's Gate. Certainly better than any dreck you'll pick up in Wyrm's Crossing.
Oh gods no. No no no. My friend, it is my turn to save you - from the disgusting tripe-garb my sister has adorned you with.
Unfortunately yes. I've been hunting him for quite some time.
How rude. I choose to devote my time unravelling reality itself, not cloth.
Easily. I was even like that, once.
Very good, sir.
Very good, ma'am.
Very good, ser.
Well, that shoudn't be particularly difficult.
Excuse me, beggars and waifs are not - oh. I see. You're not street detritus, you've merely availed yourself of my dear sister's... 'finery'.
Welcome back, friend. The fine facilities of Figaro Facemaker are yours to peruse.
Remind me again - what do you sell?
Glad to see you in good spirits, Figaro.
I thought these clothes looked rather nice.
Who are your many rivals?
A certain level of class is expected by my clientele, so if you wish to stay I must insist you purchase some less depressing garments.
HAH! The look on your face. You really thought me that tight-pocketed?
Show me something better to wear then.
Please, I look amazing in anything.
Make haste, I have a very busy day of very demanding clientele ahead. What do you require?
I'm looking to improve my attire, actually.
Let me see what you've got in stock.
They squander your most beauteous potential, and I will not stand for it.
What sort of fashion?
Perhaps I should let my butler dress me...
*Your notoriety precedes you. Prices have been moderated to reflect your less than welcome presence in the city.*
Now remember - fashion's a fickle mistress, so be sure to return.
Carmen can barely organise her own shop, never mind stage a murder mystery to meddle with me.  Very well - I'll take my precautions. Thank you.

Synopsis: Dialog with Figaro in order to access the cosmetic elements. Before and After Dolor try to kill him.
